{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17500375","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17500375"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:12:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:12:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1636"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1636","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1636"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.31,0.02,0.57,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1636"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72956"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1636","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1636"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1636"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58426"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"385"},{"type":"tags","id":"904"},{"type":"tags","id":"1109"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"3815"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9118"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1962"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15269"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30534"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72956","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72956"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old woman presents with a two day history of colicky abdominal pain and absolute constipation. Prior to this she had become increasingly constipated over the last two months, but put this down to a change in diet and iron tablets which she had started taking because she was feeling tired. She does not take any other medications. On examination her blood pressure is 128/64mmHg, pulse 90/min and temperature 37.2C. Her abdomen is distended and soft, with no localised tenderness. Some faecal pellets can be felt on digital rectal examination. A CT scan is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sigmoid volvulus","Faecal impaction","Pericolic abscess","Carcinoma of the descending colon","Ischaemic colitis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has a number of potential causes to explain her current symptoms and some form of mechanical obstruction is most likely. The scan shows a 4 cm long stenotic \u003Cstrong\u003Etumour in the mid-descending colon \u003C/strong\u003E(Image). Proximal to this point the colon is distended and full of faecal material. A sigmoid volvulus would be manifest by a massively distended loop of sigmoid arising out of the pelvis. If the underlying problem was faecal impaction, there would be a loaded rectum as well as more proximal colonic faecal loading.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere is no evidence of abscess formation and, apart from the clinical picture not suggesting such a diagnosis, if the problem was ischaemic colitis, there would be evidence of mucosal oedema and pneumatosis coli.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Worsening constipation followed by acute abdominal pain in an older patient must raise the possibility of a stenosing colonic neoplasm."],"references":["Catena F, De Simone B, Cocclini F, et al. Bowel obstruction: a narrative review for all physicians. World J Emerg Surg 2019; 14:20. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31168315/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58426"}},"quest